text:
Greenwich Street, at the N. W. corner of Albany Street. Overshadowing the street level is the old Ninth Avenue Elevated Line that was removed in 1940.

About 1900

Thomas W. Kennedy, photo
Thru Beecher Ogden
Museum Photo. Assn.

(1)

Greenwich Street, west side, north from Albany Street, showing at the N.W. corner a 3½-story building formerly known as the Planters Hotel. This building No. 122 Greenwich Street, was for a time a dry goods store; patronized by Henry Clay and other celebrities. Overhead, on Greenwich Street, is the Ninth Ave. Elevated Line.
May 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2)

The same.
May 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(3)

A view eastward on Albany Street, and showing the side of the former Planters Hotel. From that point, to the immediate foreground appear; No. 3 (2-story structure); Nos. 5 and 7; all on Albany Street. Across Greenwich Street, appears the Hamilton Building, No. 125-131 Greenwich Street, at the S.E. corner of Thames Street.
May 1925.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(4)

The same, at a later date.
May 4th, 1941.

P.L. Sperr.

Albany Street, at and adjoining the N.W. corner of Greenwich Street, showing mainly the store of a 2-story building, No. 3. On the right, across the Sixth and Ninth Ave. Elevated Lines (on Greenwich Street) appears a portion of the New York Curb Exchange Building. About 1930.
